## Example 2 — Prove a Rectangle Using Coordinates

Prove that $PQRS$ with $P(0, 0)$, $Q(6, 0)$, $R(6, 4)$, $S(0, 4)$ is a rectangle.

### Step 1: Show It Is a Parallelogram

$$\text{slope of } PQ = \frac{0 - 0}{6 - 0} = 0$$

$$\text{slope of } SR = \frac{4 - 4}{6 - 0} = 0$$

$$PQ \parallel SR \checkmark$$

$$\text{slope of } PS = \text{undefined (vertical)}$$

$$\text{slope of } QR = \text{undefined (vertical)}$$

$$PS \parallel QR \checkmark$$

### Step 2: Show a Right Angle

$PQ$ is horizontal (slope 0) and $PS$ is vertical (undefined slope). Horizontal and vertical lines are perpendicular, so $\angle P = 90°$.

### Step 3: Confirm Congruent Diagonals (Rectangle Property)

$$PR = \sqrt{(6-0)^2 + (4-0)^2} = \sqrt{36 + 16} = \sqrt{52} = 2\sqrt{13}$$

$$QS = \sqrt{(0-6)^2 + (4-0)^2} = \sqrt{36 + 16} = \sqrt{52} = 2\sqrt{13}$$

$$PR = QS \checkmark$$

✅ Answer: $PQRS$ is a **rectangle** — it is a parallelogram with one right angle (and therefore all four) and congruent diagonals.

